---

## Audit findings — flagging a mismatch with the premise

**1. Current register screen username validation — `lib/screens/register_screen.dart:34-52`**

```dart
void _onUsernameChanged(String value) {
  if (_debounce?.isActive ?? false) _debounce!.cancel();
  setState(() { _usernameAvailable = false; _usernameError = ''; });
  if (value.trim().length < 3) {
    setState(() => _usernameError = value.isEmpty ? '' : 'At least 3 characters');
    return;
  }
  setState(() => _checkingUsername = true);
  _debounce = Timer(const Duration(milliseconds: 600), () async {
    final available = await ApiService.checkUsername(value.trim());
    if (mounted) {
      setState(() {
        _checkingUsername = false;
        _usernameAvailable = available;
        _usernameError = available ? '' : 'Username already taken';
      });
    }
  });
}
```

- 600ms-debounced API check on every keystroke (after 3+ chars)
- Submit is gated: `register_screen.dart:70-73` → `if (!_usernameAvailable) { _usernameError = 'Choose an available username'; return; }`
- UI shows spinner during check, green check / red X after

**2. `ApiService.checkUsername` — `lib/services/api_service.dart:10-22`**

Hits `GET /api/check-username?username=<urlencoded>`; returns `true` iff response is 200 AND body `{"available": true}`. Any network/error/non-200 → `false` (treated as taken — fail-closed, which is the right default).

**3. "What was removed when it was disabled" — I don't see any disable**

`git log --all --follow` for `register_screen.dart` returns exactly **one** commit — the initial commit `ba0986b` on 2026-04-18 — and the debounced API check is already present at that first commit. A code-content search (`git log -S "checkUsername"`) confirms no commit ever added or removed that call after the initial one.

So either:
- (a) The check was never disabled — my audit shows it's currently live. You may be remembering a different branch, a different screen, or a plan you didn't end up executing.
- (b) It was disabled on a branch I can't see (stash, uncommitted rollback, or a branch that was reset).
- (c) Something runtime-level is bypassing it (e.g. backend `/api/check-username` always returning `available: true`, which would make it *effectively* disabled even though the client code is fine).

Before I touch anything: **can you tell me what made you think it was disabled?** If it's (c) — backend-side — the frontend plan below is still correct but incomplete (we'd need the other Claude session to fix the endpoint). If it's (a) and you just want the jason-block added on top of the already-working check, say so and I'll proceed with the reduced plan.

---

## Revised proposal

Assuming the client-side check is fine as-is and you just want the **"jason" substring block** layered on top:

| File | Change |
|---|---|
| `lib/screens/register_screen.dart` `_onUsernameChanged` | Before the 3-char / API-check path, reject if `value.toLowerCase().contains('jason')` — sets `_usernameError = 'Username not allowed'`, `_usernameAvailable = false`, skips the API call (saves a request and avoids leaking the rule to server logs) |
| `lib/screens/register_screen.dart` `_next` | Add the same jason-check as a submit-time guard (defense in depth, in case `_onUsernameChanged` didn't fire) |
| `lib/core/version.dart` | `V9` → `V10` |
| `pubspec.yaml` | `2026.4.22+2` → `2026.4.22+3` |

No change to `api_service.dart` — the endpoint call is already wired.

**Confirm (1) whether the check actually is disabled somewhere I haven't found, and (2) whether the reduced plan above matches what you want.** I won't edit until you confirm.

